<DOC><DOCNO> AP890417-0237 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 0734EST</FILEID><FIRST>d f BC-BusinessHighlights     04-17 0795</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0825</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Seventy-five years after the nation wasintroduced to Form 1040, Americans are closing anotherreturn-filing season with several million taxpayers apparentlyputting off the chore until tonight's midnight deadline.   The Internal Revenue Service promised that its walk-in officeswould remain open on the final day until every taxpayer with aquestion was served. The Postal Service went out of its way toreceive returns and make sure they were postmarked before midnight.   Taxpayers were given an extra two days to file because the April15 deadline fell on Saturday. Residents of New England and most ofNew York state have until Tuesday midnight because today is a legalholiday, Patriot's Day, in Massachusetts, site of the IRS servicecenter that receives returns from those states.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Wholesale prices rose a moderate 0.4 percentin March, the government said in a report that buoyed spirits onWall Street, where fears of spiraling inflation had risen in tandemwith earlier steep price increases.   Analysts said that while last month's restrained gain in theProducer Price Index for finished goods should allay fears thatinflation will skyrocket, it does indicate that price rises persist.   March's 0.4 percent gain, combined with steep gains of 1.0percent in January and February, works out to a compound annualinflation rate of 10.2 percent for the first quarter of 1989.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. merchandise trade deficit widenedsharply in February, the government said, bolstering economists'belief that improvement in the nation's trade performance isfizzling.   The Commerce Department said Friday the monthly, seasonallyadjusted deficit swelled 20.9 percent to $10.5 billion, up from arevised $8.68 billion in January. The deterioration reflected a 5.3percent increase in imports, which swamped a slight 0.6 percentimprovement in sales of U.S. goods abroad.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush and congressional leaders haveannounced a showpiece budget compromise to reduce the 1990 federaldeficit to under $100 billion without raising taxes.   But the pact Friday put off most hard decisions and Democraticleaders suggested it could open the way to tax increases next year.Bush called the pact a ``first manageable step'' in thedeficit-fighting journey.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Junk bond dynamo Michael Milken has agreed toset aside about $700 million of his assets to guarantee payment ifhe is convicted of fraud and racketeering charges in thegovernment's largest-ever securities prosecution.   The former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. financier also wasordered Friday to post a $1 million bond and surrender his passportin exchange for his freedom until an expected trial later this yearculminating Wall Street's insider trading scandals.</TEXT><DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   State and federal officials dissectedExxon's cleanup plan for hundreds of miles of shoreline as anenvironmentally risky steam-cleaning method was tested on rocksblackened by America's worst oil spill.   Oil from the 10.1 million-gallon spill, mostly in the form oftar balls and mousse-like foam, on Sunday threatened Homer andother ports on fish-rich Cook Inlet. In Kodiak, the nation's No. 1fishing port, herring from a closed fishery were examined forcontamination.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   International Business Machines Corp. said itsfirst-quarter profit rose 1.8 percent excluding an accountingchange, and the stock market responded favorably to the news.   The gain Friday came in spite of a chip problem that caused adelay in shipment of mainframe computers, the biggest and mostprofitable part of IBM's product line. IBM's stock rose $1.62{ to$110.87{ in consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading,contributing to Wall Street's best day since October.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   General Motors Corp. Chairman Roger Smithreceived about $3.6 million in salary and benefits last year,placing last in terms of compensation among the chiefs of thenation's Big Three automakers, GM said.   In its annual proxy statement issued Friday, the nation'slargest automaker said Smith received $983,000 in salary, exercised$1 million in stock options and had $68,833 contributed by thecompany to a savings and stock purchase plan.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   The stock market ran up its sharpest gain in nearly six monthsFriday, inspired by an apparent easing of inflationary pressures.The Dow Jones industrials average jumped 41.06 to 2,337.06, for itsbest single-day showing since it rose 43.92 points last Oct. 20.   The dollar finished mostly lower in light domestic dealings.   The bond market had its best day since early December.   Fears that drought conditions will persist for another year inthe Midwest drove grain and soybean futures prices up sharply onthe Chicago Board of Trade. Coffee futures surged; platinum gainedwhile gold and silver futures retreated; petroleum prices rose; andlivestock and meat futures were mostly higher.</TEXT></DOC>